Process for Developing Methodology

This case methodology has changed drastically over the course of only a week. This problem truly made me think and look 
for new methods and approaches to problems I have seen many times before. My original plan was to use a series of API calls to 
deterministically ascertain each location for a given company’s facilities, as well as the type of the address. The goal was also 
to extract company-specific features such as the industry, specialties, size, and description along with the facility location information. 
I found this unique combination of APIs by a series of google searches for inputs and desired outputs. 

I originally meant to iterate through a series of HTML webpages for a given website, to find an “about us” field. 
Upon further strategization, it proved to be extremely inconsistent from one company’s website to another, as well as 
expansive to get the HTTP for each webpage and efficiently “jump” between them. I began looking for an API that could take a company 
and return key features about it, including the locations of its facilities. I thought about how company profiles on LinkedIn, and 
found that LinkdAPI has similar behaviors. I chose to use the “company lookup” endpoint (which takes our given company name in plaintext), 
and feed that result to a call to its “company details” endpoint. This returns a dictionary of company-level information, as well as an 
array of locations with field such as street address, city, geographic area, country, zip code. I began searching for another API I could 
feed these addresses to in order to determine facility type, and I found Nominatim OpenStreetMap API. This process proved to be much less 
straightforward than I initially thought. Some issues that arose quickly:
- Different address fields were present for different locations
- Addresses are formatted differently in different countries (can confuse Nominatim)
- The street address field + the company name together would confuse Nominatim
- Sometimes the street address would have only a number, street name, or not be a present field at all
- Nominatim makes it difficult to search for a company name and address at same time (these are two different kinds of queries) 
- Searching for company name and region alone may return multiple results
- Searching using only address and not guide query with the company name - may return another nearby building/facility 
not associated with the location we are aiming to find/classify
The pipeline I developed to error-handle and acknowledge these limitations was to build a query using 
Company name + geographic area + country + zip code to use on Nominatim geocoder endpoint. Then, if the street address had a streetname 
and number (not just one or the other or empty field), I would try the query again with the street address instead of the company name. 
Since the goal was to use the “addresstype” field returned 
by Nominatim’s JSON response, if this street address query was not successful, I would geocode using GeoApify’s forward geocoding endpoint 
and feed that proper address to Nominatim, requery, and get the “address” field. If this third attempt was unsuccessful, due to API request 
limits and time constraints, I set the address type “unknown”. If I had more time to revisit and refine this project, I would add another 
layer of intelligence to infer the location type from the majority facility type for that location, cluster similar companies and their 
location types, or use more information from another source about that company’s facilities. I originally was using the Overpass Openstreetmap 
API to geocode because it returned a more detailed address type, but these field names changed or were often not present. The consistency of 
Nominatim an GeoApify geocoding API’s return schema made it more stable for use in this project with many different companies. If it were used 
for only certain cases, it is possible the Overpass Openstreetmap API would have predictable behavior. 

After the location/facility-specific columns were determined for the current company, the “goodness of fit” for Tractain ICP was the next 
information compute. After working with and building other RAG systems in past projects, I immediately formalized this problem as a use case 
for a vectorized database an LLM could query to ground insights in a pre-defined Tractian-specific ground truth. I wanted to compute a 
structured score based on my interpretation of the most important criteria for Tractian ICP from reading over the Tractian website and
examining past and current companies Tractian has worked with. I wanted to average this structured score with an LLM-with-RAG
implementation. I also asked the LLM agent the 6 criteria I was using to determine the final score. I created a vectorized database 
with “documents” from various excerpts about Tractain’s mission, typical clients, use cases, and previous clients. I was also going
to include the ICP scores given in the demonstrated examples of the case study as examples. Averaging the structured scores
(each of 6-fold score determined based on keyword search and semantic search using embeddings) with LLM-with-RAG score would
introduce human review, transparent scoring, and a defined source of truth from Tractian information. In addition to providing the LLM 
access to the Tractian ICP vectorized database, 6-part scoring criteria from my own review of Tractian ICP guidelines, and company-specific 
features (company description, industry, industry grouping, specializations, number of employees, number of facilities, typical facility type,
 and company website – all pulled from given information and features extracted from “company details” endpoint of LinkdAPI query. 
Unfortunately, due to compute resources and free API credentials, I had to do away with my methodology to utilize RAG. I didn’t have access 
to OpenAI or Google geocoding API’s due to paid plans for these tools. No pre-built HuggingFace LLM would make inferences quickly enough 
(even after making adjustments to my algorithm, number of tokens, size of the vectorized database, or size of each document in vectorized 
database). Once I let it run long enough (several minutes for one company), the LLM would always score a 0, but the runtime and complexity of
the problem led me to explore other alternatives. I scored companies using only the aforementioned structured score, using semantic search 
for industry, and keyword searches within other company-specific features extracted from the API to determine a score for each feature. I 
weighted these features based on my own interpretation of Tractian criteria. I also stored a value in each row for the highest scoring 
feature for that particular company to provide more insight into the score. As I was unaware of the limitations to an unpaid LinkdAPI 
account, I unknowingly ran out of credentials of my training phase (even in making 3 accounts with 3 separate emails) and decided to 
submit the project as-is. In order to get an output table (written to a CSV), there are instructed in the provided repository about how 
to run the script. The READMe contains instructions on which API keys are needed and how they should be stored into environmental variables. 

I am more than happy to explain any other details of my existing methodology or future works upon request. Please see diagrams, 
brainstorming notes, and other details in my handwritten outline in the repository’s “TractianStudy_MethodsBrainstorming.pdf” file. The companies
I included in the script are only an example, which I expect to have a variety of scores due to the range of their industries and company-specific features. 



